Predicate in Java

Predicate is a functional interface that takes one input and returns a boolean value.

👉 Used to test a condition

Syntax
Predicate<T>

👉 where T — тип входного значения

Basic Example
import java.util.function.Predicate;

Predicate<Integer> isEven = x -> x % 2 == 0;

System.out.println(isEven.test(4)); // true
Main Method
test()
boolean result = predicate.test(value);

👉 returns true or false

Combining Predicates
and()
Predicate<Integer> greaterThan10 = x -> x > 10;
Predicate<Integer> isEven = x -> x % 2 == 0;

Predicate<Integer> combined = greaterThan10.and(isEven);

combined.test(12); // true
or()
Predicate<Integer> p = greaterThan10.or(isEven);
negate()
Predicate<Integer> notEven = isEven.negate();
Example with Collections
List<String> list = List.of("Apple", "Banana", "Avocado");

list.removeIf(s -> s.startsWith("A"));

👉 uses Predicate inside

Real Use Cases
filtering data
validation
conditions in streams
Example with Stream
list.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.length() > 5)
    .forEach(System.out::println);
Why use Predicate?
reusable conditions
cleaner code
works perfectly with lambda and streams
Summary
Predicate → input → boolean
main method: test()
supports combining (and, or, negate)
widely used in filtering and streams
